{"add":{"doc":{"id":"476bf29f0a38802fba0b229fc0e0afe23bdd6e8fe92578d779413a70459db456","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/64/Medieval_Arab_Palestine.jpg/220px-Medieval_Arab_Palestine.jpg","previous":[],"after":["The Greek toponym Palaistínē (Παλαιστίνη), with which the Arabic Filastin (فلسطين) is cognate, first occurs in the work of the 5th century BCE Greek historian Herodotus, where it denotes generally[38] the coastal land from Phoenicia down to Egypt.[39][40] Herodotus also employs the term as an ethnonym, as when he speaks of the 'Syrians of Palestine' or 'Palestinian-Syrians',[41] an ethnically amorphous group he distinguishes from the Phoenicians.[42][43] Herodotus makes no distinction between the Jews and other inhabitants of Palestine.[44] The Greek word bears comparison to a congeries of ancient ethnonyms and toponyms. In Ancient Egyptian Peleset/Purusati[45] has been conjectured to refer to the \"Sea Peoples\".[46][47] Among Semitic languages, Assyrian Palastu generally refers to an undefined area.[48] Biblical Hebrew's cognate word Plištim,[49] is usually translated Philistines.[50]"]}}}